{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"The request sent to the external API always includes the complete list of valid taxonomy labels.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Failure boundary is module handoff (request builder -> API client). A unit test of only a helper could miss wiring/serialization omissions at dispatch time. Integration-brake: no real OS/network requirement (stub transport is sufficient), no dependence on model judgment, no multi-step agent chain. Rejection-gate: System rejected because behavior text is about request contents, not real network behavior; Agentic rejected because no correctness claim depends on model output quality.","test_description":"Wire classifier with a fake API transport that records outbound payload. Call classify() with a taxonomy, assert the dispatched request contains every allowed label exactly as expected.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.35,"Integration":0.55,"System":0.07,"Agentic":0.03,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"When the API returns a label that is not in the taxonomy, the module returns \"unknown\" instead of forwarding the unexpected value to the caller.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"This is normalization/validation logic on returned label values; the specific failure is local decision logic, not infrastructure interaction. MOCK-MISS check: behavior can fail inside one function/object even with direct fixture input. Rejection-gate: Integration rejected because behavior text does not require module-to-module state handoff to manifest; Agentic rejected because this uses a fixed synthetic API label, not model quality.","test_description":"Call the normalization/classification decision path with taxonomy [legal, technical, financial, other] and raw label \"medical\"; assert final result is \"unknown\".","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.72,"Integration":0.24,"System":0.02,"Agentic":0.02,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"For identical raw API responses, the module's normalization step always produces the same final label.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"Determinism of normalization is a pure local property. No I/O, no external dependency, no cross-module handoff required to expose this failure.","test_description":"Invoke normalization repeatedly with identical raw response fixtures and taxonomy; assert stable identical output across runs.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.9,"Integration":0.08,"System":0.01,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"On repeated live API calls for the same document and taxonomy, the returned label remains consistent unless the provider response itself changes.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"Pass 1 INTENT TAG: model-output. Pass 2 LABEL MAP: Agentic. Behavior explicitly depends on repeated live AI responses and consistency of returned labels; mocks would hide true model/provider variance. Rejection-gate: Workflow rejected because calls are repeated single-step classifications, not a chained multi-agent pipeline.","test_description":"Run N real provider calls for identical document+taxonomy, capture raw provider outputs and final labels. Assert label stability whenever raw provider response is unchanged; allow divergence only when provider response differs.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.0,"Integration":0.04,"System":0.22,"Agentic":0.72,"Workflow":0.02}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"Request construction enforces the configured token budget before dispatch (for example truncate/reject according to policy).","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Failure boundary is module handoff between budget enforcement and dispatch. Need wiring-level assertion that dispatch is blocked or payload modified per policy. Integration-brake: no real OS/network/subprocess required; no model-output correctness dependency; no multi-step agent chain. Rejection-gate: System rejected because behavior text is pre-dispatch enforcement, which in-process fakes can reproduce exactly.","test_description":"Configure low token budget; run classify with oversized input using fake transport. Assert policy behavior (truncate/reject) and that any dispatched payload conforms to budget, or that no dispatch occurs when rejection policy applies.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.4,"Integration":0.52,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0.03,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":6,"description":"Provider-reported token usage for a typical document stays within the configured per-call budget.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"Pass 1 INTENT TAG: model-output (provider-produced usage metadata from real AI call). Pass 2 LABEL MAP: Agentic. A stubbed provider can always return in-budget usage and hide real provider accounting/tokenization mismatches. Rejection-gate: Workflow rejected because this is a single-call check, not multi-step agentic sequencing.","test_description":"Execute real classification calls for representative document(s), read provider-reported token usage from response metadata, and assert usage <= configured budget.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.06,"System":0.35,"Agentic":0.56,"Workflow":0.02}},{"behavior_id":7,"description":"When the API signals that the request rate is too high, the module waits and retries rather than returning an error to the caller.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"This is retry orchestration across local modules (error handling, backoff policy, API client). A deterministic fake API returning rate-limit then success can expose real failures. Integration-brake: no mandatory real OS/network/subprocess needed; no dependence on model judgment; no multi-step agentic pipeline.","